‘optimus atque Fuscus' v. 82 of this Satire. The arguments, which are strong for taking ‘ optimus' in these cases with the following name, do not apply equally here. It is more usually taken with ‘ Pedius.’ Those who believe that the two were brothers sometimes (as Diur.) take it ἀπὸ κοινοῦ with both. Very possibly the additional name is intended to recall the pure Roman descent to which they are truc in their native Ro- man speech. The cognomen of Pub— licola belonged to the Valeria gens and so to Messalla. Cp Virg. Catal. 11 (ad Messallam) 40 ‘Messallis Publicolis? It may have belonged to Pedius either, according to the Scholiasts' theory, as a member by birth of the Valeria gens or, as Estte suggests, on the female side from the Valeria who married Q. Pedius.

30. Canusini . . . bilinguis. The Schol. tells us that both Ennius and Lucilius had given the title ‘ bilingues' to the ‘Bruttates' or ‘ Bruttii,' doubt- less in the same sense, as speaking Greek as well as the native Italian dialect. For Canusium see Sat. 1. 5. 91, 92
